@undefined -- Re: your question, a real-world example would be comparing the US Constitution vs the PRC (China) Constitution.
US Constitution + Amendments -- While the US Constitution does enumerate federal scope, it is framed with many provisions that limit federal governmental power and ensure that the individual‚Äôs rights and agencies are safeguarded.
PRC Constitution -- While the PRC Constitution does enumerate rights (it actually enumerates many citizen rights, a phenomenon many in the Western mainstream media are not willing to admit/highlight), it is framed within the context of serving the collective interest and promoting social stability.

@undefined  -- Excellent points you make. Sure, these comparisons are not absolute. There is a Yin vs Yang...Yin most of the time but with bit of Yang; Yang most of the time but with a bit of Yin. On movement: that's a good point. We are already seeing Trump's USA and PRC moving to converge somewhat in terms of being tech-nationalist-capitalist-mercantilist. The Network State movement (it being a movement) would be moving too. Balaji has time and time again also emphasized the importance of re-centralization and following core leadership.
